{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778174820,"nonce":"rL7xujK7F8tcS0tvcBL7ShaxEkk=","message":"**Settled design — 2026-05-07.**\n\nThree orthogonal decisions, all settled in conversation:\n\n## Decision 1 — Linearisation regime: BOTH\n\n- **Trajectory linearisation (LTV) — primary.** Roll a nominal reach (no disturbance), linearise at every timestep. Yields `(A_t, B_{w,t}, C_{z,t}, D_t)` for t ∈ [0, T]. Matches H∞ Riccati's finite-horizon framing exactly; round-trip test against `solve_hinf_riccati` is a literal equality.\n- **Fixed-point linearisation (LTI) — auxiliary.** Newton-solve for closed-loop equilibrium (`f(x*) - x* = 0`), linearise there. Reports the idealised held-state regime.\n- Reason for both: agreement when trajectory has a long hold tail = network cleanly settles to its equilibrium (a useful diagnostic). Disagreement = the two answer different questions and we want both numbers.\n\n## Decision 2 — Channel definitions\n\n### `w` (disturbance input) — report all three:\n\n1. **Additive force on point mass** (flavor (a)). Standard `ẋ = Ax + Bu + B_w w`, plug into standard H∞ pipeline. Matches APT/minimax adversary.\n2. **Sensory noise on observed state**. Perturbation to RNN's input rather than plant's force. Requires extracting the sensor-input pathway from the closed loop.\n3. **Structural `ΔA` plant uncertainty** (flavor (b)). Multiplicative, not additive: `ẋ = (A + ΔA)x + Bu`. *Different machinery from 1+2* — small-gain framing or μ-analysis. Treated as v2 in the same build (user requested v1+v2 simultaneously). Load-bearing channel for the (a) ⊊ (b) test on existing networks.\n\n### `z` (performance output) — report all four:\n\na. `Q·state + R·control` — **headline.** Cost-matched to Riccati. Only `z` for which `γ_RNN` is literal-comparable to `γ*_Riccati`.\nb. `u` (control output) — gain from disturbance to control effort.\nc. `state error` — deviation of perturbed-trajectory state from unperturbed nominal of same controller; `x_t - x̄_t`.\nd. **Peak forward / peak lateral velocity** (separate scalars, NOT a ratio) — behavioural channels per C\u0026S Fig 1e. Use the corrected metric from `f90bf74` (`peak_forward_velocity` = signed projection on reach axis; `peak_lateral_velocity` = orthogonal speed).\n\n`z` is just a `(C_z, D)` matrix on top of the `(A, B_w)` linearisation — cheap to swap, cheap to report multiple.\n\n## Decision 3 — Algorithm: BOTH\n\n- **Hamiltonian bisection** — runs on the LTI fixed-point linearisation (Boyd–Balakrishnan 1990). Cheap, mature; one number per checkpoint per channel pair. Use `scipy.signal` or equivalent.\n- **Power iteration** on the LTV trajectory operator. Treat `T: w → z` as a tall linear operator on length-N signals; largest singular value is the `L₂→L₂` induced gain. Iterate forward sweep + adjoint sweep + renormalise. Native to JAX; gives worst-case `w*` trajectory as byproduct.\n\n**Care points for power iteration:**\n- 3–5 random restarts; take max (avoid converging to second-largest singular value when top two are close).\n- Renormalise `w_k ← w_k / ‖w_k‖_2` between iterations.\n- Convergence test: stop when relative change in gain estimate \u003c 1e-6 for two consecutive iterations.\n- Adjoint sweep runs *backward* in time; structure as `lax.scan` and use `jax.linear_transpose` or VJP. Easy to flip a sign — unit-test on a hand-computed 2-state LTV before trusting on full plant.\n- Finite-horizon `L₂` over `[0, T]`, NOT infinite-horizon.\n\n**Internal consistency check:** Hamiltonian gain on the trajectory tail (last-timestep `(A_T, B_{w,T}, C_{z,T}, D_T)`) ≈ power-iteration gain on a long-hold trajectory.\n\n**External round-trip test:** Drop a Riccati-computed LTI controller into the analyser's controller slot; verify analyser gain matches `find_gamma_star`'s γ* within tolerance for the `Q+R` `z` channel. This is the test that lets us trust nonlinear-RNN gain numbers downstream.\n\n## Out of scope (this build)\n- Running on real Part 2.5 RNN checkpoints — separate analysis pass after the analyser lands.\n- Frequency-domain transfer-function plots / Nyquist diagrams — possibly future, not v1+v2.\n\n## File layout\n- `src/rlrmp/analysis/induced_gain.py` — main module.\n- `tests/test_induced_gain.py` — unit tests (toy 2-state LTV, round-trip, internal consistency, channel sanity).\n\n## Auth dependency\nThis branch is based on `feature/peak-forward-velocity-metric` (issue `f90bf74`, auth `420a122c` pending) since the analyser uses `peak_forward_velocity` / `peak_lateral_velocity` from the corrected metric. Auth submission for the analyser must wait for `420a122c` to land in main first.","files":null}]}